sec.p:
In the analyses presented here we identify shortened and lengthened genes according to these criteria: 

cutoff on the expression levels of the gene (in both conditions):

\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$FPKM_{PRE} > 1 $$ \end{document}FPKMPRE>1

a roar value >1 (shortening) or <1 (lengthening). Note that negative or undefined values of m/M or roar could occur in some situations - such as counts equal to zero for PRE or POST portions - and are discarded
the Bonferroni corrected1 Fisher test p-value <0.05 for single samples analyses, while for multiple samples cases we require that all samples crossings result in a nominal p-value <0.05

Assuming the equiprobability of read distribution (that is each nucleotide has the same probability of finding itself in a read) the efficiency in generating reads of the two isoforms is proportional (with a constant k) to their lengths: 
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$\epsilon_{M} = k (l_{PRE}+l_{POST}) $$ \end{document}εM=k(lPRE+lPOST)
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$\epsilon_{m} = k (l_{PRE}) $$ \end{document}εm=k(lPRE)

Defining l
PRE as the length of the PRE portion and l
POST as the length of the POST we can now obtain the number of reads falling on the two portions as: 
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$\#r_{PRE} = \epsilon_{M} M \left(\frac{l_{PRE}}{l_{PRE}+l_{POST}}\right) + \epsilon_{m} m $$ \end{document}#rPRE=εMMlPRElPRE+lPOST+εmm and: 
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$\#r_{POST} = \epsilon_{M} M \left(\frac{l_{POST}}{l_{PRE}+l_{POST}}\right) $$ \end{document}#rPOST=εMMlPOSTlPRE+lPOST

We start from: 
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$\left\{ \begin{array}{lr} \#r_{PRE} = & \epsilon_{M} M \left(\frac{l_{PRE}}{l_{PRE}+l_{POST}}\right) \\[0.3cm] & + \epsilon_{m} m \\[0.25cm] \#r_{POST} = & \epsilon_{M} M \left(\frac{l_{POST}}{l_{PRE}+l_{POST}}\right) \end{array} \right. $$ \end{document}#rPRE=εMMlPRElPRE+lPOST+εmm#rPOST=εMMlPOSTlPRE+lPOST

Then with simple algebraic steps the system can be solved yielding the formula to obtain m/M using only read counts and lengths: 
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$m/M = \frac{l_{POST} \#r_{PRE}}{l_{PRE} \#r_{POST}} -1 $$ \end{document}m/M=lPOST#rPRElPRE#rPOST−1

Portion lengths should be corrected to keep into account read lengths and the assignment to POST of spanning reads, therefore: 
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
